===Etymology 2===
{{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|hrēowan}}, perhaps influenced by {{etyl|non|en}} {{term|hryggja||to distress, grieve|lang=non}}<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary|rue}}</ref>, from Germanic. Cognate with Dutch {{m|nl|rouwen}}, German {{m|de|reuen}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|rues|ruing|pres_ptc2=rueing|rued}}

# {{context|obsolete|transitive|lang=en}} To cause to [[repent]] of sin or regret some past action.
# {{context|obsolete|transitive|lang=en}} To cause to feel [[sorrow]] or [[pity]].
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[repent]] of or [[regret]] (some past action or event); to [[wish]] that a past action or event had not taken place.
#: ''I '''rued''' the day I crossed paths with her.''
#* {{rfdate}} Chapman
#*: I wept to see, and '''rued''' it from my heart.
#* {{rfdate}} Milton
#*: Thy will chose freely what it now so justly '''rues'''.
# {{context|archaic|intransitive|lang=en}} To feel [[compassion]] or [[pity]].
#* '''Late 14th century''' Geoffrey Chaucer, ‘The Franklin's Tale’, ''Canterbury Tales''
#*: Madame, '''reweth''' upon my peynes smerte
#* {{rfdate}} Ridley
#*: which stirred men's hearts to '''rue''' upon them
# {{context|archaic|intransitive|lang=en}} To feel [[sorrow]] or [[regret]].
#* {{rfdate}} Tennyson
#*: Old year, we'll dearly '''rue''' for you.

